hook.real_world_problem:
You need to sort an array of Product objects by price. Easy with primitive arrays — `Arrays.sort(nums)`. But for objects, Java needs to know: what does 'less than' mean for a Product?

For Strings: alphabetical order. For Integers: numeric order. For Products: you define it.

Java's `Comparable` interface is the answer:

```java
class Product implements Comparable<Product> {
    ...
    @Override
    public int compareTo(Product other) {
        return Double.compare(this.price, other.price);
    }
}

// Now this works:
Product[] products = { ... };
Arrays.sort(products);  // sorts by price — you defined the rule
```

`Comparable` is an INTERFACE — a contract that says 'this class can be compared.' When you implement it, you're telling Java's sorting algorithm: 'here's how to compare two Products.'

This is interfaces in real use. Not theoretical — this sorts actual product catalogs at Flipkart, Amazon, and every e-commerce backend. And it's just one of dozens of standard Java interfaces you'll use daily. Today you learn them all.

concept_explanation.intro:
An **interface** is a PURE CONTRACT — a collection of method signatures without implementations.

Think of an interface as a job description: 'Anyone who takes this role MUST be able to do these things.' The interface doesn't care HOW — just that it CAN be done.

```java
public interface Drawable {
    void draw();                    // abstract by default — no 'abstract' keyword needed
    void setColor(String color);
}

public interface Resizable {
    void resize(double factor);
    double getSize();
}
```

Key rules:
- Interface methods are `public abstract` by default — no modifier needed
- Interface CANNOT have instance fields (only `public static final` constants)
- Interface CANNOT have constructors
- A class IMPLEMENTS an interface with the `implements` keyword
- A class must provide a body for ALL interface methods
- A class CAN implement MULTIPLE interfaces (unlike extends — only one class)

concept_explanation.implements_keyword:
```java
class Circle implements Drawable, Resizable {
    private String color;
    private double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) { this.radius = radius; }

    // Must implement ALL methods from Drawable:
    @Override
    public void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing " + color + " circle"); }

    @Override
    public void setColor(String color) { this.color = color; }

    // Must implement ALL methods from Resizable:
    @Override
    public void resize(double factor) { radius *= factor; }

    @Override
    public double getSize() { return radius; }
}
```

Circle implements BOTH Drawable AND Resizable — TWO interfaces. Java allows this because interfaces are contracts, not inheritance of state. There's no ambiguity about where fields come from (there aren't any).

**Using the interface as a type**:

```java
Drawable d = new Circle(5);  // Circle IS Drawable
d.draw();                     // calls Circle's implementation
// d.resize(2);               // COMPILE ERROR — resize not in Drawable

Resizable r = new Circle(5); // Circle IS Resizable
r.resize(2);                  // OK
// r.draw();                  // COMPILE ERROR — draw not in Resizable
```

Each interface reference only exposes the methods defined in that interface.

concept_explanation.multiple_interfaces:
**Multiple interface implementation** is the most important structural advantage of interfaces over abstract classes:

```java
// A class can only EXTEND one class:
class Manager extends Employee { ... }           // extends one
// class Manager extends Employee, Person { }   // ILLEGAL

// But can IMPLEMENT many interfaces:
class Employee implements Comparable<Employee>, Serializable, Printable {
    ...
    @Override public int compareTo(Employee o) { ... }
    // Serializable has no methods to implement
    @Override public void print() { ... }
}
```

This enables a class to fulfill MULTIPLE roles without the complexity of multiple inheritance:
- `Comparable<Employee>` → can be sorted
- `Serializable` → can be saved to disk/network
- `Printable` → can be printed

Think of interfaces as ROLES or CAPABILITIES. A Dog can be a Pet (Trainable, Lovable) AND a WorkingDog (SearchAndRescue, Tracking). A PaymentService can be Loggable, Auditable, Retryable. The class inheritance hierarchy describes WHAT it IS; the interfaces describe WHAT IT CAN DO.

**Important**: if two implemented interfaces have methods with the same name and signature, the class provides ONE implementation that satisfies both. If they conflict in return type or have incompatible contracts, you must use `default` method resolution (covered next).

concept_explanation.interface_constants:
Interfaces can have constants — `public static final` by default:

```java
public interface HttpStatus {
    int OK = 200;           // implicitly public static final
    int CREATED = 201;
    int NOT_FOUND = 404;
    int SERVER_ERROR = 500;
}

// Any class implementing OR just using HttpStatus gets these:
System.out.println(HttpStatus.OK);  // 200
```

This pattern was common before Java enums. Modern Java prefers enums for related constants. But you'll see interface constants in legacy code — know what they are.

**Note**: using an interface just for constants (no methods) is considered an anti-pattern ('Constant Interface anti-pattern'). Prefer enums or utility classes.

concept_explanation.default_methods:
Java 8 added **`default` methods** to interfaces — methods WITH a body:

```java
public interface Collection<E> {
    void add(E element);    // abstract — must implement
    int size();             // abstract — must implement

    default boolean isEmpty() {   // concrete — FREE implementation
        return size() == 0;
    }

    default void addAll(Collection<E> other) {  // concrete
        // iterate other and call add()
    }
}
```

Default methods exist for BACKWARD COMPATIBILITY. When Java 8 added stream() and forEach() to Collection, they couldn't make them abstract (every existing class would break). Default methods gave a default implementation that existing classes could either keep or override.

**Using default methods**:

```java
interface Printable {
    String getContent();  // abstract

    default void print() {  // default — concrete
        System.out.println(getContent());
    }

    default void printWithBorder() {
        System.out.println("--- " + getContent() + " ---");
    }
}

class Report implements Printable {
    private String content;
    public Report(String content) { this.content = content; }

    @Override
    public String getContent() { return content; }  // must implement abstract
    // print() and printWithBorder() are inherited for free!
}
```

**Difference from abstract class**: abstract class can have state; interface default methods can't access any fields (there are none). Default methods only call other interface methods.

concept_explanation.comparable_interface:
**`Comparable<T>`** is the interface that enables natural ordering for a class. Implementing it means: 'my objects have a natural sort order.'

```java
public interface Comparable<T> {
    int compareTo(T other);
}
```

`compareTo` returns:
- **Negative**: `this` should come BEFORE `other`
- **Zero**: they're EQUAL
- **Positive**: `this` should come AFTER `other`

**Common pattern**: use existing `compare` methods:

```java
class Product implements Comparable<Product> {
    private String name;
    private double price;

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Product other) {
        return Double.compare(this.price, other.price);  // ascending price
    }
}

Product[] products = { new Product("Keyboard", 1999), new Product("Mouse", 599) };
Arrays.sort(products);  // sorts by price — uses compareTo
```

**Double.compare vs subtraction**: NEVER use `return this.price - other.price` for doubles — floating-point precision errors can cause wrong results. ALWAYS use `Double.compare(this.price, other.price)` for doubles. For integers: `Integer.compare(this.score, other.score)` or `this.score - other.score` (only for ints where overflow isn't a concern).

concept_explanation.programming_to_interface:
'Program to interfaces, not implementations' — the most-cited Java best practice:

```java
// BAD: bound to ArrayList specifically
ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();

// GOOD: programmed to interface
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();  // can swap to LinkedList, etc.
```

Why it matters:

```java
// If you use List<String>:
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
// Later: swap with ZERO code changes:
List<String> names = new LinkedList<>();  // change ONE line
// All calling code using names.add(), names.get() works unchanged

// If you used ArrayList<String>:
ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();
// Later: need LinkedList → change everywhere the type appears
```

In method signatures, this is EVEN MORE IMPORTANT:

```java
// Method accepting interface:
public void processNames(List<String> names) { ... }  // works with ANY List

// Method accepting implementation:
public void processNames(ArrayList<String> names) { ... }  // ONLY works with ArrayList
```

Programming to interfaces enables:
- Flexibility: easy to swap implementations
- Testability: inject mock implementations in tests
- Decoupling: caller doesn't depend on a specific class

**In Spring**: your service classes receive dependencies as interface types (`@Autowired UserRepository repo`). The framework injects the concrete implementation. Change the implementation without touching the calling code.

concept_explanation.interface_inheritance:
Interfaces can EXTEND other interfaces:

```java
public interface Animal {
    void breathe();
}

public interface Pet extends Animal {
    void respondToName();
}

// Implementing Pet requires implementing BOTH methods:
class Dog implements Pet {
    @Override public void breathe() { System.out.println("..."); }
    @Override public void respondToName() { System.out.println("Woof!"); }
}
```

This is how Java extends existing interfaces. `List extends Collection extends Iterable`. The full chain means implementing List requires implementing all methods from all three.

And a class can extend a class AND implement interfaces simultaneously:

```java
class SortedProductList extends AbstractList<Product> implements Comparable<SortedProductList>, Serializable {
    // extends one class, implements two interfaces
}
```

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
public interface Printable {
    String format();

    default void print() {  // free default method
        System.out.println(format());
    }
}

public interface Validatable {
    boolean isValid();

    default void checkValidity() {  // default convenience
        if (!isValid()) {
            System.out.println("[WARNING] Invalid: " + this);
        }
    }
}
```

Two interfaces with abstract methods and useful defaults. Any class implementing them gets `print()` and `checkValidity()` for free.

```java
class Product implements Comparable<Product>, Printable, Validatable {
    private String name;
    private double price;
    private int stock;

    public Product(String name, double price, int stock) {
        this.name = name;
        this.price = price;
        this.stock = stock;
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public double getPrice() { return price; }
    public int getStock() { return stock; }

    // Comparable — natural sort by price
    @Override
    public int compareTo(Product other) {
        return Double.compare(this.price, other.price);
    }

    // Printable — formatted output
    @Override
    public String format() {
        return name + " — ₹" + price + " (" + stock + " in stock)";
    }

    // Validatable — business rules
    @Override
    public boolean isValid() {
        return name != null && !name.isBlank()
            && price > 0
            && stock >= 0;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() { return format(); }
}
```

Three interfaces implemented. Each adds a distinct ROLE to Product — sortable, printable, validatable.

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public static void main(String[] args) {
    Product[] catalog = {
        new Product("Keyboard", 1999.0, 15),
        new Product("Mouse", 599.0, 45),
        new Product("Monitor", 18999.0, 8),
        new Product("", -1, -5)  // invalid product
    };

    // Comparable — sort by natural order (price)
    Arrays.sort(catalog);
    System.out.println("=== Sorted by price ===");
    for (Product p : catalog) {
        p.print();  // from Printable default method
    }

    // Polymorphism via interface type
    System.out.println("\n=== Via Printable reference ===");
    Printable[] printables = catalog;  // Product IS Printable
    for (Printable p : printables) {
        System.out.println(p.format());
    }

    // Validatable
    System.out.println("\n=== Validation ===");
    for (Product p : catalog) {
        p.checkValidity();  // from Validatable default — only prints if invalid
    }
    System.out.println("Valid products: " + countValid(catalog));
}

static int countValid(Validatable[] items) {
    int count = 0;
    for (Validatable v : items) if (v.isValid()) count++;
    return count;
}
```

Notice `countValid` takes `Validatable[]` — it doesn't know Products exist. ANY validatable class works with this method.

worked_example.final_code:
import java.util.Arrays;

interface Printable {
    String format();
    default void print() { System.out.println(format()); }
}

interface Validatable {
    boolean isValid();
    default void checkValidity() {
        if (!isValid()) System.out.println("[WARNING] Invalid: " + this);
    }
}

class Product implements Comparable<Product>, Printable, Validatable {
    private String name;
    private double price;
    private int stock;

    public Product(String name, double price, int stock) {
        this.name = name;
        this.price = price;
        this.stock = stock;
    }

    public String getName() { return name; }
    public double getPrice() { return price; }
    public int getStock() { return stock; }

    @Override
    public int compareTo(Product other) {
        return Double.compare(this.price, other.price);
    }

    @Override
    public String format() {
        return name + " — ₹" + price + " (" + stock + " in stock)";
    }

    @Override
    public boolean isValid() {
        return name != null && !name.isBlank() && price > 0 && stock >= 0;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() { return format(); }
}

public class ProductCatalog {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Product[] catalog = {
            new Product("Keyboard", 1999.0, 15),
            new Product("Mouse", 599.0, 45),
            new Product("Monitor", 18999.0, 8),
            new Product("", -1, -5)
        };

        Arrays.sort(catalog);
        System.out.println("=== Sorted by price ===");
        for (Product p : catalog) p.print();

        System.out.println("\n=== Validation ===");
        for (Product p : catalog) p.checkValidity();
        System.out.println("Valid: " + countValid(catalog));
    }

    static int countValid(Validatable[] items) {
        int count = 0;
        for (Validatable v : items) if (v.isValid()) count++;
        return count;
    }
}
